        },
        {
            "text": "Nearly 3 billion people around the globe are restricted by COVID-19 and many will die. These are predicted to be times of great economic loss, potentially in excess of a trillion US dollars. Some argue that the world will never be the same, and Suzy Taherian [12] suggests that supply chains will be local rather than global. In future we will shop, work, and play online, with the digital divide becoming a chasm. Healthcare for all will become the norm. Cities it is claimed will alter as a response to radically changed urban life [13] . As alluded to in an earlier editorial [14] , urban planners face a tension between densification and disaggregation. As Jack Shenker points out \"if proximity to one\"s job is no longer a significant factor in deciding where to live, for example, then the appeal of the suburbs wanes; we could be heading towards a world in which existing city centres and far-flung \"new villages\" rise in prominence, while traditional commuter belts fade away.\"",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 259,
                    "end": 263,
